\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Performance Data Collection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall maintain continuous,
 accurate collection of service performance data as the operational foundation of this policy.
 Performance data collection shall be systematic,
 automated where technically supported by the designated work order system,
 and sufficient to support the SLA adherence measurements,
 deviation analyses,
 and reports defined in this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Work Order System as System of Record
\series default
:
 The designated work order system (Redmine) is the authoritative source for all service level performance data.
 IT Department personnel shall ensure that all triage completions,
 response actions,
 escalation events,
 and closure decisions are recorded in the work order system with timestamps accurate to the minute.
 No performance measurement activity shall rely on data sources that are not traceable to the work order system or a formally designated supplementary monitoring tool approved by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Data Collection Intervals
\series default
:
 For work orders subject to Critical or Urgent severity commitments,
 the Assistant IT Director shall verify adherence status no less than every four (4) business hours from triage completion.
 For High severity work orders,
 adherence status shall be verified no less than daily.
 Normal and Low severity work orders shall be reviewed in aggregate no less than weekly.
 These intervals represent minimum monitoring frequency;
 continuous automated alerting,
 where available,
 shall supplement but not replace these review obligations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Required Data Elements
\series default
:
 For each closed work order,
 the following elements shall be captured and retained to support SLA adherence measurement:
 (a) work order identifier and submission timestamp,
 (b) assigned severity level at triage completion and triage completion timestamp,
 (c) response action timestamp and responding technician,
 (d) resolution or escalation timestamp and disposition,
 (e) any reclassifications with documented rationale,
 (f) asset support classification (IT-Managed,
 IT-Supported,
 or Vendor-Managed) as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 and (g) escalation chain and vendor contact timestamps where applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Automated Monitoring Tools
\series default
:
 Where automated monitoring tools are deployed to support service delivery,
 the Assistant IT Director shall ensure that tool outputs are integrated with the work order system or formally reconciled against it at minimum weekly.
 Tool configurations and data collection parameters shall be reviewed no less than annually by the Assistant IT Director and approved by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 SLA Adherence Monitoring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall maintain ongoing visibility into SLA adherence across all active work orders,
 using the performance data defined in Section 6.1 and the service level commitments established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Adherence Tracking
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall maintain a current adherence view of all open work orders that are within or approaching their response or resolution windows.
 This view shall be updated continuously from the work order system and shall be accessible to IT Department personnel for self-monitoring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
At-Risk Identification
\series default
:
 A work order shall be classified as At-Risk when 75% or more of its applicable response or resolution window has elapsed without the required action being completed.
 At the time of At-Risk classification,
 the assigned technician shall be notified by the Assistant IT Director and the work order status shall be flagged in the system.
 The assigned technician shall acknowledge the At-Risk flag and provide a written status update within one (1) business hour of notification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Breach Detection
\series default
:
 A work order shall be recorded as an SLA Breach when the applicable response or resolution commitment has not been met by the deadline established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 All SLA Breaches shall be recorded in the work order system with a Breach designation,
 the breach timestamp,
 and the technician of record at time of breach.
 SLA Breaches are distinct from formal escalations;
 a work order may breach a commitment and remain under active remediation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Trend Monitoring
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall review SLA adherence trends no less than monthly,
 examining breach rates by severity level,
 by technician,
 by asset support classification,
 and by service category.
 Trend data shall be incorporated into the monthly summary report defined in Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Deviation Thresholds and Corrective Action Protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Not all SLA deviations require the same response.
 This section establishes the thresholds at which a deviation escalates from a work order management issue to a documented operational deficiency requiring formal action,
 and defines the required response at each threshold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Threshold 1 —
 Individual Breach (Operational Response)
\series default
:
 A single SLA Breach shall trigger an At-Risk review at next-business-hour by the Assistant IT Director.
 The Assistant IT Director shall document the cause in the work order record and determine whether the breach resulted from (a) resource or workload conditions,
 (b) a process or triage failure,
 (c) a vendor response gap,
 or (d) an approved exception.
 No formal corrective action plan is required for an isolated breach,
 but the cause documentation shall be retained and counted toward threshold calculations below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Threshold 2 —
 Severity-Weighted Breach Rate (Formal Review)
\series default
:
 When the SLA breach rate for any individual severity level exceeds ten percent (10%) of all work orders at that severity level within any rolling thirty (30) calendar day period,
 the Assistant IT Director shall initiate a formal review.
 The formal review shall be documented in writing,
 completed within five (5) business days of threshold detection,
 and submitted to the IT Director.
 The review shall identify systemic causes,
 affected services or personnel,
 and recommended remediation.
 The IT Director shall approve or direct modifications to the recommended remediation within five (5) business days of receipt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Threshold 3 —
 Sustained Non-Compliance (Corrective Action Plan)
\series default
:
 When a formal review under Threshold 2 identifies the same root cause for the second consecutive thirty-day period,
 or when the breach rate for any severity level exceeds twenty percent (20%) in any single thirty-day period,
 a formal Corrective Action Plan (CAP) shall be initiated under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The CAP shall be assigned to the Assistant IT Director,
 approved by the IT Director,
 and tracked to closure.
 Open CAPs shall be reported in the monthly performance summary defined in Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Vendor-Specific Deviation
\series default
:
 When a vendor governing an IT-Supported asset fails to meet contracted SLA terms and the failure results in an IT breach of the referral or escalation commitment defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 the Assistant IT Director shall document the vendor failure separately from the IT breach record.
 Vendor performance data shall be maintained as defined in Section 6.5.
 Sustained vendor SLA failures shall be escalated to the vendor compliance framework under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Service Level Reporting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall produce and distribute service level performance reports on the following cadences,
 with the defined content and distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Weekly At-Risk and Open Ticket Summary
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall produce a brief internal summary each week identifying all open work orders classified as At-Risk,
 all open SLA Breaches in active remediation,
 and any Threshold 2 formal reviews in progress.
 Distribution is internal to IT Department personnel.
 This report is an operational tool and shall be retained as a transitory record until no longer administratively useful,
 in accordance with applicable retention schedules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monthly Performance Summary Report
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall produce a formal Monthly Performance Summary Report and submit it to the IT Director no later than the fifth (5th) business day of the following month.
 This report shall include,
 at minimum:
 (a) total work orders opened and closed by severity level;
 (b) SLA compliance rate by severity level,
 expressed as a percentage of work orders meeting both response and resolution commitments;
 (c) breach count and breach rate by severity level;
 (d) open Corrective Action Plans and their current status;
 (e) vendor SLA performance summary as defined in Section 6.5;
 (f) Recurring Ticket analysis as defined in Section 6.6;
 and (g) any notable trends or anomalies requiring IT Director attention.
 The IT Director shall review and acknowledge each Monthly Performance Summary Report within five (5) business days of receipt.
\end_layout

